<br>
Kathy<br>
<br>
*  *  *<br>
<br>
-- As your hosting company *before* you register about CPU cycles.  Keep records of who you talked to about this and exactly what they said. We found that CPU cycles are often the major bottleneck, even for a small message board. <br>
<br>
-- If possible, try to get your hosting company to provide some links to other sites they host.  Often, they'll give you a few that are comparable to what you're planning. Other times, they use the &quot;We don't divulge that for privacy&quot; schtick. That's utter BS, and we would avoid a host that won't show you their product.<br>
<br>
-- Consider using Invisionboard, if at all possible. It’s utterly delightful software, with only a few small defects.  Our last upgrade took less than five minutes.<br>
<br>
-- We recommend you plan on using twice as much bandwidth as you do now, for growth. Make sure your hosting company lets you upgrade if you need to, and has an affordable plan that has quadruple your current usage.<br>
<br>
-- In a related vein, you might check your hosting company’s overusage fees. That is, if you *need* an extra GB of bandwidth in a month, how much is it going to cost you?<br>
<br>
-- Be sure to ask them about what tools they have installed; most importantly, MySQL. Also, if at all possible, make sure your host has phpMyAdmin installed. It’s not *strictly* necessary, but, as you probably know, it makes your life much easier.<br>
<br>
-- Make sure your host provides shell access, and install some sort of log compiler that generates real time stats. Ask how often you can run cron jobs, which will help you trace attacks against your site. <br>
<br>
-- Don’t feel bad if your first host doesn’t work out as you planned. It happens (boy, does it happen!). In a related vein, you might have a backup choice ready.<br>
<br>
-- Pay by credit card so you can fight any unfair charges.<br>
<br>
-- Have a figure of what you’re willing to pay, and ask a few people to help out looking for hosting. Which you’re already doing, from what I can see.<br>
<br>
-- Try not to get bogged down into a long-term contract unless absolutely necessary. <br>
<br>
-- Avoid, at all costs, any plan that offers unlimited bandwidth or unlimited hard drive space. It’s a lie.<br>
<br>
--Some indepenent sites provide lists and ratings of host companies<br>
<br>
Good luck with the search!!!<br>
